Is it mandatory for a lambda expression to have parameters?

No, it is not mandatory for a lambda expression to have parameters. The syntax of a lambda expression allows for three types of lambda expressions:


Lambda expression with parameters:
(parameters) -> { body }


Lambda expression with a single parameter:
parameter -> { body }


Lambda expression with no parameters:
() -> { body }

You can use an empty parameter list when the lambda expression does not require any input. The absence of parameters is denoted by the empty parentheses ().

Here are examples of each type of lambda expression:
// Lambda expression with parameters
(int a, int b) -> { return a + b; }

// Lambda expression with a single parameter
x -> { return x * x; }

// Lambda expression with no parameters
() -> { System.out.println("Hello, Lambda!"); }
